<title>Paper Scout Research Report - 2026-06-25</title>

<p>This run kept circling the same question: what does it take to make embodied agents robust enough to leave the lab? Three very different works gave overlapping answers, each from a different angle. <b>RoboTwin 2.0</b> shows that the bottleneck is often the data itself—specifically, whether synthetic demonstrations cover the visual and physical chaos of real scenes. <b>Foresight</b> argues that even good policies fail, so the urgent problem is detecting failure early and cheaply enough to do something about it. And Jiayi Weng's <b>Learning Beyond Gradients</b> asks whether the whole premise of learning a monolithic policy is the wrong target: maybe the durable artifact is maintainable, testable code. Together they map a pipeline—generate robust data, watch for failure, keep the system explainable—that is more engineering doctrine than single algorithmic breakthrough.</p>

<callout emoji="✅" background-color="light-green" border-color="green">
  <p><b>Standout:</b> RoboTwin 2.0 is the clearest seed for a scalable sim-to-real data engine. The released simulator, object library, and code-generation loop are real, and the hardest-condition sim-to-real gains are large even if the headline percentages are cherry-picked.</p>
</callout>

<h1>Theme 1: Building robust embodied data</h1>

<p>The dominant source of fragility in robot learning is still the gulf between training scenes and deployment scenes. This period produced several attempts to close that gap at the data layer.</p>

