<p>The headline numbers need context. The abstract's 367% relative improvement and 228% zero-shot gain come from the unseen-background + cluttered corner case. The average absolute gain across all four conditions is a still-respectable +24.4 percentage points (17.0% → 41.4%), but final success rates remain below 50% in most conditions. Synthetic data clearly buys robustness, yet the robot still fails more often than it succeeds in the hardest setting.</p>

<p>Embodiment-aware grasp adaptation is the most cleanly validated mechanism after domain randomization. Table 2 shows large gains for low-DoF arms—Piper +22.7% and Aloha-AgileX +13.7%—while high-DoF Franka and UR5 change little. That matches the code, where <code>grasp_perfect_direction</code> and <code>rotate_lim</code> are embodiment-specific config fields.</p>

<callout emoji="❗" background-color="light-yellow" border-color="yellow">
  <p><b>Caveat:</b> The sim-to-real numbers are conditional on scene feasibility—the eval loop only tests policy rollouts on seeds where the expert program already succeeds. That is reasonable for benchmarking, but it means the reported rates are not unconditional success on arbitrary scenes.</p>
</callout>

<h1>Theme 2: Knowing when the policy is failing</h1>

<p>If the first theme is about making better data, the second is about admitting that policies still fail and building a watcher that notices in time. <b>Foresight</b> (arXiv 2606.23085) uses action-conditioned world-model latents to detect failures in long-horizon manipulation.</p>

<hr/>

<h2>Foresight: failure detection from predicted latents</h2>

<p>The key insight is that a failure is often not visually anomalous in isolation; it is a mismatch between what the policy intended to do and what the world actually did. Foresight therefore conditions its failure signal on the action chunk. It builds on V-JEPA 2-AC, a latent action-conditioned world model: a frozen ViT-Giant encoder observes an 8-frame context, and a trained 24-layer causal Transformer predictor forecasts future <i>latent representations</i> given the policy's action chunk. The model never decodes pixels; it predicts where the encoder's own representation should go.</p>

<p>At each replan step the predicted latent <latex>z_t^p</latex> is mean-pooled to 1408 dimensions, projected, and fed as a timestep token into a small causal Transformer detector. The detector outputs a per-timestep failure score <latex>s_t \in [0,1]</latex>, trained only on trajectory-level binary labels because exact failure timestamps are unknown. Temporal aggregation is essential: an MLP detector is near chance on real-world data, while the causal Transformer reaches ROC-AUC 0.93 on ReactorX/ACT and 0.89 on Franka/GR00T N1.5.</p>

<p>The thresholding uses functional conformal prediction (FCP). From successful calibration rollouts the method builds a time-varying threshold <latex>\delta_t = \mu_t + \hat{q} \cdot \sigma_t</latex>, where <latex>\mu_t</latex> and <latex>\sigma_t</latex> are the mean and standard deviation of detector scores at time <latex>t</latex>, and <latex>\hat{q}</latex> is the <latex>(1-\alpha)</latex>-quantile of the nonconformity scores. Under exchangeability this controls the false-positive rate on successful rollouts at level <latex>\alpha</latex>. The authors sweep many <latex>\alpha</latex> values and select the one that maximizes cross-validated balanced accuracy; selected values range from 0.02 on LIBERO-Long to 0.20 on BEHAVIOR-1K.</p>

