<p>The gains scale with horizon length: the strongest result is on BEHAVIOR-1K, where rollouts average 8,557 steps and Foresight improves balanced accuracy by +0.14 over the best baseline. That is exactly where you would expect predicted-latent mismatch to become informative.</p>

<p>The cost, however, is dominated by the world-model backbone. On an H200 the ViT-G encoder takes ~122 ms and the predictor ~60 ms per replan, for a feature-extraction subtotal of ~183 ms. The detector head adds less than 1 ms. For a chunk-based policy that already replans every 100–1000 ms this is acceptable; for high-frequency reactive control it is not. Edge deployment is also hard: the full backbone is 1.3B parameters.</p>

<callout emoji="❗" background-color="light-yellow" border-color="yellow">
  <p><b>Caveat:</b> No official Foresight code is public as of this run. The V-JEPA 2-AC backbone was cloned and inspected, but integration details—exact early-detection weighting, action-chunk alignment across policies, and FCP extrapolation past calibration length—remain author-authority only.</p>
</callout>

<h1>Theme 3: A different notion of learning</h1>

<p>The third thread steps back and asks whether the right artifact to optimize is a neural network at all. Jiayi Weng's <b>Learning Beyond Gradients</b> frames <i>Heuristic Learning (HL)</i> as an alternative loop: state → action → feedback → code edit, where the object being updated is software structure rather than weights.</p>

<hr/>

<h2>Learning Beyond Gradients: code as the learnable object</h2>

<p>Weng's argument is that coding agents are now good enough to read failures, edit code, add tests, and watch replays. A Heuristic System (HS) therefore contains not just a policy but detectors, feedback channels, <code>trials.jsonl</code> logs, regression tests, videos, and an update mechanism. The update is a direct code edit by an LLM, not backpropagation.</p>

<p>The artifact repo is unusually concrete. I reproduced the Breakout progression exactly: 387 → 507 → 839 → 864, matching the blog's numbers on <code>envpool==1.2.5</code>. A single Ant MPC episode scored 5820.5, inside the blog's reported 5-episode range. The policies are not toy if-statements; they are engineered control systems with PD controllers, residual MPC, computer-vision pipelines, and finite-state machines.</p>

